    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 36,
    "last_activity_date" : 1415021788,
    "creation_date" : 1415021788,
    "answer_id" : 26715506,
    "question_id" : 7485670,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>You have to include classpath to your javac and java commands</p>\n\n<pre><code>javac -cp . PackageName/*.java\njava -cp . PackageName/ClassName_Having_main\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>suppose you have the following </p>\n\n<p>Package Named: com.test\nClass Name: Hello (Having main)\nfile is located inside \"src/com/test/Hello.java\"</p>\n\n<p>from outside directory: </p>\n\n<pre><code>$ cd src\n$ javac -cp . com/test/*.java\n$ java -cp . com/test/Hello\n</code></pre>\n\n<ul>\n<li>In windows the same thing will be working too, I already tried</li>\n</ul>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 95302,
      "reputation" : 3928,
      "user_id" : 1392690,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 79,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/9c5Wg.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "JohnMerlino",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1392690/johnmerlino"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1421243858,
    "creation_date" : 1421243858,
    "answer_id" : 27944662,
    "question_id" : 7485670,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>This problem occurred for me when I imported an existing project into eclipse. What happens is it copied all the files not in the package, but outside the package. Hence, when I tried run > run configurations, it couldn't find the main method because it was not in the package. All I did was copy the files into the package and Eclipse was then able to detect the main method. So ultimately make sure that Eclipse can find your main method, by making sure that your java files are in the right package.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 137055,
      "reputation" : 1627,
      "user_id" : 340992,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d56929f509b19b2aec8a1b62648260db?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Zsolti",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/340992/zsolti"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1424439396,
    "creation_date" : 1424439396,
    "answer_id" : 28630285,
    "question_id" : 7485670,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I use Anypoint Studio (an Eclipse based IDE). In my case everything worked well, until I found out that while running the java code, something totally different is executed. Then I have deleted the .class files. After this point I got the error message from this question's title. Cleaning the project didn't solve the problem.</p>\n\n<p>After restarting the IDE everything worked well again.</p>\n"
  }, {
