    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 151,
    "last_activity_date" : 1510572469,
    "last_edit_date" : 1510572469,
    "creation_date" : 1427647227,
    "answer_id" : 29331827,
    "question_id" : 7485670,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>If the class is in a package</p>\n\n<pre><code>package thepackagename;\n\npublic class TheClassName {\n  public static final void main(String[] cmd_lineParams)  {\n     System.out.println(\"Hello World!\");\n  } \n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Then calling: </p>\n\n<pre><code>java -classpath . TheClassName\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>results in <code>Error: Could not find or load main class TheClassName</code>. This is because it must be called with its fully-qualified name:</p>\n\n<pre><code>java -classpath . thepackagename.TheClassName\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>And this <code>thepackagename</code> directory must exist in the classpath. In this example, <code>.</code>, meaning the current directory, is the entirety of classpath. Therefore this particular example must be called from the directory in which <code>thepackagename</code> exists. </p>\n\n<p>To be clear, the name of this class is not <code>TheClassName</code>, It's <code>thepackagename.TheClassName</code>. Attempting to execute <code>TheClassName</code> does not work, because <em>no class having that name exists</em>. Not on the current classpath anyway.</p>\n\n<p>Finally, note that the compiled (<em>.class) version is executed, not the source code (</em>.java) version. Hence “CLASSPATH.”</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1478247,
      "reputation" : 186,
      "user_id" : 1390610,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 14,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/5GqG9.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "don",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1390610/don"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1431461318,
    "creation_date" : 1431461318,
    "answer_id" : 30200485,
    "question_id" : 7485670,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>If so simple than many people think, me included :)</p>\n\n<p>cd to <strong><code>Project Folder/src/package</code></strong> there you should see yourClass.java then run <strong><code>javac yourClass.java</code></strong> which will create yourClass.class then cd out of the <em><code>src</code></em> folder and into the <em><code>build</code></em> folder there you can run <strong><code>java package.youClass</code></strong></p>\n\n<p>I am using the Terminal on Mac or you can accomplish the same task using Command Prompt on windows</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1665827,
      "reputation" : 151,
      "user_id" : 1533247,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 70,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/jLvVD.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Argyle Ghost",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1533247/argyle-ghost"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1433592332,
    "creation_date" : 1433592332,
    "answer_id" : 30682628,
    "question_id" : 7485670,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>If you are using Eclipse... I renamed my main class file and got that error.  I went to \"Run As\" configurator and under the class path for that project, it had listed both files in the class path.  I removed old class that I renamed and left the class that had the new name and it compiled and ran just fine.</p>\n"
  }, {
